    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-09T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-09T10:00:00-05:00" n="743"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d743">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6731/207: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Istanbul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-09T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 9, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. Reference Department’s telegram No. 49, July 1, 4 p.m. (last paragraph) and
                    Embassy’s despatch No. 294, July 13.<note n="5" xml:id="d743fn5">Latter not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The private secretary of the Minister of Economy has handed our Commercial
                    Attaché the following list of commodities on which the Turkish Government is
                    desirous of obtaining tariff reductions from the United States: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Figs.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Rugs, carpets and kilims.</item>
                        <pb facs="0958" n="947" xml:id="pg_947"/>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Mohair.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Hazelnuts, shelled and unshelled.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Walnuts, shelled and unshelled.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>Pistachio nuts, shelled and unshelled.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>Pine nuts (kernels), shelled.</item>
                        <label>8.</label>
                        <item>Olive oil in containers weighing less than 40 pounds and in containers
                            weighing 40 pounds or more.</item>
                        <label>9.</label>
                        <item>Almonds, shelled and unshelled. 10. Tobacco.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>At the same time there was also communicated the following list of articles of
                    American origin and manufacture in which the Turkish Government will grant
                    tariff reductions: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Machinery.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Motors.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Automobiles and trucks.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Radios.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Typewriters.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>Rubber goods, including automobile tires, mechanical goods, et
                            cetera.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>[File copy not signed]</closer>
            </div>
